<HEADLINE>
<P>
FORD WANTS TO DOUBLE NUMBER OF HISPANIC DEALERS BY MID-'90S 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JAMES RISEN, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
DETROIT 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ford said Friday that it plans to try to double the number of its 
Hispanic-owned auto dealerships by the mid-1990s in a move to bolster its 
position within the growing Hispanic market. 
</P>
<P>
The program is similar to efforts by Ford and the other domestic auto makers to 
increase the number of black-owned car dealerships around the country. It also 
follows criticism by some minority groups of Japanese auto makers for their 
failure to open up import dealership opportunities to blacks and other 
minorities. 
</P>
<P>
But unlike the domestic industry's black dealership efforts, which were 
developed partly under pressure from the Rev. Jesse Jackson's Operation Push, 
Ford officials said they have not been working with any Hispanic organizations 
to create the dealership program. 
</P>
<P>
"We believe there are Hispanics with automotive experience and the financial 
capability to acquire a dealership; however it will be our job to find 
dealership opportunities for these individuals," said Robert Rewey, vice 
president for Ford's sales operations. "Ford will provide operational support 
and training for individuals who meet our appointment qualifications." 
</P>
<P>
Ford said it currently has 40 Hispanic-owned dealerships and is aiming to 
increase that to at least 80 by the mid-1990s. A Ford spokesman did not know 
how many of the existing Hispanic dealerships are in California. 
</P>
<P>
Overall, Ford said it now has 316 minority-owned dealerships around the nation. 
</P>
<P>
Rewey observed that Hispanics now represent 7.7% of the U.S. population and are 
forecast to become the nation's largest minority by 2010. "It has been 
estimated that Hispanics have $160 billion in disposable income, and that 
figure will grow considerably during the next decade," he added. 
</P>
<P>
A Ford spokesman said the attempt to expand the number of Hispanic-owned 
dealerships should help Ford's marketing efforts in areas like Southern 
California that have large Hispanic populations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
AUTOMOBILE DEALERS; FORD MOTOR CO; HISPANICS; MINORITY OWNED BUSINESS; 
MARKETING 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
