<HEADLINE>
<P>
AVON PLANNING TO SELL GIORGIO AND PARFUMS STERN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARTHA GROVES, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Avon Products on Friday put up for sale Giorgio Beverly Hills and Parfums 
Stern, the booming prestige fragrance subsidiaries that it bought with much 
fanfare in 1987. 
</P>
<P>
Proceeds would be used to reduce Avon's $1-billion debt, much of which was 
incurred after an ill-fated diversification four years ago into health-care 
businesses, spokesman John Cox said. 
</P>
<P>
Diana K. Temple, an analyst with Salomon Bros. in New York, speculated that 
Avon could get $400 million for the two units, which have four of the top 10 
selling fragrances in the United States: Giorgio Beverly Hills, Red from 
Giorgio Beverly Hills, Oscar de la Renta and Uninhibited by Cher. Other brands 
include Perry Ellis, Valentino and Deneuve. 
</P>
<P>
Cox emphasized that Avon has not formally decided to sell the units but rather 
has hired the investment banking firm of Morgan Stanley &amp; Co. to evaluate 
offers. 
</P>
<P>
He declined to comment on speculation that Michael Gould, 46, president and 
chief executive of the units, might attempt a buyout. Gould, based in Giorgio 
Beverly Hills' Santa Monica headquarters, could not be reached for comment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
